#cuda
#gpu

Before Diving into the field of CUDA Programming lets start by understanding how did we got here. In 2001/2003 researchers started to see GPU as data-parallel coprocessors thus starting the field of GPGPU. But they had to use Graphics APIs like OGL and DX 11 for doing general purpose computing so Nvidia released CUDA. In recent years latest graphics APIs like DX 12 and Vulkan have supported Compute Shaders and introduced new compute pipelines.

In a typical C/C++ program we write a serial code on CPU which may access the file system memory. But in CUDA programming we write a serial code that invokes millions on threads on the GPU. It does the processing and gives back the final result to the CPU. 

![[Pasted image 20250907130825.png]]

This is called Heterogenous Computing. In this field we call CPU as host and GPU as device. Host and device have separate memories. A CUDA program will contain both host and device code. 
__Kernel__ is a data parallel function that runs on the GPU. Its invoked on the CPU. Lets take a look at a vector add example 

```c
// Kernel defination
__global__ void vectorAdd(const float* A,
	const float* B, float* C)
{
	int i = threadIdx.x;
	C[i] = A[i] + B[i];
}

int main()
{
	// ...
	// Kernel invocation with N Threads
	vectorAdd<<<1,N>>>(A, B, C);
}
```

In the above example of `__global__` is declaration specifier, it states that these function shall run on the GPU and will be invoked on the CPU. CUDA provides us the `threadIdx` keyword that tells us the thread index of the current kernel. `<<<>>>>` are called chevron brackets they are used to configure the way threads shall be launched on the GPU. In our case we are simply launching N threads. A typical CUDA program execution is as follows: 

```
CPU Serial Code
		|
GPU Parallel Kernel
KernalA<<<blocks, threads>>>(args);
		|
CPU Serial Code
		|
GPU Parallel Kernel
KernalB<<<blocks, threads>>>(args);
```

We will talk about blocks and grids later

| Name         | Executed on | Only Callable From |
| ------------ | ----------- | ------------------ |
| `__global__` | Device      | Host               |
| `__device__` | Device      | Device             |
| `__host__`   | Host        | Host               |

`__global__` functions must return void. Each thread on GPU returning say a `int` won't make sense. Also `__device__` functions are inlined by default. For all the device code there should not be static variables and no `malloc()` is allowed. All the math functions available in C are also available in CUDA ([Full Reference Manual](https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-c-programming-guide/index.html#mathematical-functions-appendix)).

# CUDA Threads and Blocks
In CUDA we want to execute millions or billions of threads in parallel but there are real world limitations like number of cores/transistors that we can fit on a chip, power (heat generated and the cooling required) and scheduling these millions/billions of threads (Yay! We can solve this using good software practices and hardware). We can't run _all_ of these threads at once. So how can we schedule them?
- Group threads into __BLOCKS__
- Scheduler works on __BLOCKS__ not __THREADS__
- Blocks can be executed independently, they __DONT SHARE RESOURCES__
- Each GPU Kernel can execute many blocks

So what are blocks?
- They are a Array of threads. Each block can have upto 1024 threads.
- Each block in a grid (collection of blocks) has same number of threads each with identical configuration.
- Each thread in a block can __SYNCHRONIZE__ and it can access __SHARED MEMORY__
- Blocks and grids can be 1 D, 2 D, 3 D
- Each thread in a block reside in the same streaming multiprocessor (CORE) 
- Block Index - `blockIdx`
- Block Size - `blockDim`
- Each block executes independently. They can execute in any order. They may execute in parallel or in serial manner. They are scheduled in any order by any number of core. 

Each software thread maps to a CUDA core on the hardware. In order to identify the threads we have `threadIdx`. In order to get the global unique value of the thread:

```
Thread ID of index (x, y, z) = x + y * BlockDim.x + z * BlockDim.x * BlockDim.y
```

Below is an example of blocks of varous sizes.
![[Pasted image 20250907133926.png]]
A __Grid__ is nothing but collection of blocks and we can get the size of the grid with `gridDim`.

Lets take a look at matrix addition where we use a single block. 

```c
__global__ void MatrixAddition(const float* A, const float* B, float* C)
{
	int idx = threadIdx.x + threadIdx.y * blockDim.x;
	C[idx] = A[idx] + B[idx];
}

int main()
{
	//...
	// Kernel invocation with one block of N*N*1 threads
	int blocks = 1;
	dim3 threadsPerBlock(N, N);
	MatrixAddition<<<blocks, threadsPerBlock>>>(A, B, C);
}
```

In the above code listing we are launching a single block called  `threadsPerBlock` with following dims

```c
threadsPerBlock.x = N;
threadsPerBlock.y = N;
threadsPerBlock.z = 1;
```

And are accessing the unique thread index via the equation mentioned before. But there is an problem, each block can have atmost 1026 threads. So our matrix size will have an upper limit. In order to resolve this we can launch multiple blocks. 

```c
__global__ void MatrixAddition(
	const float* A,
	const float* B,
	const float* C,
	int N
)
{
	int x = blockIdx.x * blockDim.x + threadIdx.x;
	int y = blockIdx.y * blockDim.y + threadIdx.y;
	int idx = y * N + x;
	C[idx] = A[idx] + B[idx];
}

int main()
{
	// ...
	// Kernel infocation with computed configurations
	dim3 threadsPerBlock(16, 16);
	dim3 block(N/threadsPerBlock.x, N/threadsPerBlock.y);
	matrixAddition<<<blocks, threadsPerBlock>>>(A, B, C, N);
}
```

In the above example we are dividing our (N, N) matrix into blocks of (16, 16). So say we had a matrix of size (32,32) we will get a grid of blocks with size (2,2) with `blockIdx` range of  `()[0,1], [0,1])`. We will have 16 x 16 threads per block ie  ` threadIdx ` will be in range of ` ([0, 15], [0, 15]) ` 

```c
int i = blockIdx.x * blockDim.x + threadIdx.x;
// i = [0, 1] * 16 + [0, 15];
min_i = 0 * 16 + 0 = 0;
max_i = 1 * 16 + 15 = 32;

int j = blockIdx.y * blockDim.y + threadIdx.y;
// j = [0, 1] * 16 + [0, 15];
min_j = 0 * 16 + 0 = 0;
max_j = 1 * 16 + 15 = 32;
```

As we had mentioned previously CUDA doesn't guarantee how blocks will be scheduled within a Streaming multiprocessor and how they will be ordered and how they will be executed. This allows to to scale our programs as seen below. This is called transparent scalablity 

![[Pasted image 20250907142051.png]]
# CUDA Memory Introduction

The CPU has access to the RAM and SSD whereas GPU has access to VRAM and High band width memory (HBM) so if we want to process data that on the CPU's registers/caches/RAM/SSD then we will have to transfer it to the GPU. The CPU (host) can transfer from/to the GPU (device). On the GPU there are following kinds of memory (conceptually as far as programmers are concerned)
- Constant
- Texture (We wont deal with this)
- Global
![[Pasted image 20250907142724.png]]
CUDA provides functions for handing memory on the device
1. `cudaMalloc()` allocated global memory on the device
2. `cudaFree()` frees that memory

```c
float* device_memory = NULL;
int size = width*height*sizeof(float); // size in bytes
cudaMalloc((void**)&device_memory, size);
// ...
// do the work
// ...
cudaFree(device_memory);
```

3. `cudaMemcpy()` copy the memory, there are four directions for it: 
		A. Host to device : `cudaMemcpyHostToDevice`
		B. Host to host: Traditional C `memcpy()`
		C. Device to host: `cudaMemcpyDeviceToHost`
		D. Device to device: `cudaMemcpyDeviceToHost`

# Parallel SAXPY using CUDA

SAXPY means Single Precision A.X + Y
In our case we have:
Input: 
- Vectors: X and Y (32 bits floats)
	- N element each 
- Scalar: A
Output:
- Vector: Z (32 bits float)
	- N elements
Operation:
- Elementwise : `Z = A*X+Y`

Lets start with a simple C implementation of it:
```c
void saxpy(
	int n,
	float a, 
	float* restrict x,
	float* restrict y,
	float* z
)
{
	for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
	{
		z[i] = a*x[i] + y[i];
	}
}

int main()
{
	// ...
	saxpy(1<<20, 2.0, x, y, z);
}
```

This program is linear ie O(N), although it can be optimized if multithreading is done correctly, but the cuda program will have O(1), guess why?

Now lets take a look at CUDA program:

```c
#define N (1 << 20) // 1 million elements

__global__ void saxpy(
	int n, 
	float a, 
	const float* x, 
	const float* y,
	float* z
)
{
	int i = blockIdx.x * blockDim.x + threadIdx.x;
	if(i < n)
	{
		z[i] = a*x[i] + y[i];
	}
}

int main()
{
	int size = N * sizeof(float);
	// Allocate and initialize x, y, z on Host
	// ...
	float *device_x; 
	float *device_y; 
	float *device_z;

	// allocate memory on device for device_x, device_y and device_z
	cudaMalloc((void**)&device_x, size);
	cudaMalloc((void**)&device_y, size);
	cudaMalloc((void**)&device_z, size);

	// copy from host to device
	cudaMemcpy(device_x, host_x, size, cudeMemcpyHostToDevice);
	cudaMemcpy(device_y, host_y, size, cudeMemcpyHostToDevice);

	// 4096 * 256 = 1 million
	saxpy<<<4096, 256>>>(N, 2.0, device_x, device_y, device_z);

	// copy result back to CPU
	cudaMemcpy(host_z, device_z, size, cudaMemcpyDeviceToHost);
}
```


# Parallel Matrix Multiplication using CUDA

![[Pasted image 20250907150619.png]]

In matrix multiplication where P = M x N,
`P[i][j] = dot_product(M[i], N[j])` where dot product is sum of element wise multiplication of `M[i] and N[j]`

Lets take a look at C Code
```c
void MatrixMultiplyOnHost(
	float* M, 
	float* N, 
	float* P, 
	int width
)
{
	for(int i = 0; i < width; i ++)
	{
		for(int j = 0; j < width; j++)
		{
			float sum = 0;
			for(int k = 0; k < width; k++) // dot product
			{
				float a = M[i * width + k]; // (i, k)
				float b = N[k * width + j]; // (k, j)
				sum += a + b;
			}
			P[i*width + j] = sum;
		}
	}
}
```

So can we do this in CUDA? Yes the above code is highly penalizable since there are inter-dependencies and input and output is well structured. 

```c
__global__ void MatrixMultiplication(
	const float* device_m,
	const float* device_n,
	float* device_p,
	const int width
)
{
	int tx = threadIdx.x;
	int ty = threadIdx.y;
	// (x, y) => ty * width + tx;
	
	float pValue = 0;
	
	for(int k = 0; k < width; k++)
	{
		float m = device_m[ty*width + k]; // (k, ty)
		float n = device_n[k*width + tx]; // (tx, k)
		pValue = m+n;
	}
	
	device_p[ty*width + tx] = pValue;
}

int main()
{

//	1. Allocate and initialize M, N and result P matrices
//		Copy M, N matrices to device

	int size = width*width*sizeof(float);
	float *device_m;
	float *device_n;
	float *device_p;
	
	cudaMalloc((void**)&device_m, size);
	cudaMalloc((void**)&device_n, size);
	cudaMalloc((void**)&device_p, size);
	
	cudaMemcpy(device_m, host_m, size, cudaMemcpyHostToDevice);
	cudaMemcpy(device_n, host_n, size, cudaMemcpyHostToDevice);
//  2. M*N on the device

	dim3 threads(width, width)
	dim3 blocks(1,1);
	MatrixMultiplication<<<blocks, threads>>( device_m, device_n,
											device_p, width );
	
//	3. Copy matrix P to host and output 
//		Free device memory and clean up
	cudaMemcpy(host_p, device_p, size, cudaMemcpyDeviceToHost);
	cudaFree(device_m);
	cudaFree(device_p);
	cudaFree(device_n);
}
```

# Scheduling threads

As we had discussed before in a GPU there are core, each core executes a thread. These cores are called __STREAMING PROCESSOR__ and collection of them are called __STREAMING MULTIPROCESSORS__. Also we know that blocks can have at max. 1024 threads and each block runs on a single SM. 

Similarly each thread occupies a lane. A collection of 32 lanes is termed as __WARP__. So warp is collection of 32 __CONSECUTIVE__ threads. Thus each block consists of many blocks. So we have to keep the block size as multiples of 32. Otherwise last warp of every block will have wasted threads. 

When scheduling, the GPU schedules the warps and not threads.

> NOTE: ALL THREADS IN A WARP EXECUTE SAME INSTRUCTION AT THE SAME TIME

When scheduling the warps, there is zero-overhead for context switching. All the resources resize on the same SM until execution completes. `warpSize` stores size of warp. 

**![](data:image/png;base64,)**

- If we don't have enough warps to keep GPU busy then we are wasting resources. 
During branch divergence the threads are split. 
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**
In G80, There were 8 SPs in a single SM, then how could CUDA do 32 lanes per warp?. Well pipelining group of 8 threads. So it would take 4 cycles to dispatch a warp. 
# Synchronizing threads

We know that threads in a block can synchronize. In order to do that we have to create a barrier. Until all the threads in the block react it the threads will wait, after that all shall continue. We call `__syncthreads` to create this barriers. 

```c
A[i] = B[j];
__syncthreads();
func(A[i], A[i+1]);
```

__NOTE: Never call `__syncthreads()` inside a condition until you know that all threads will hit it__ 

```c
if(threadIdx.x > m)
{
	__syncthreads(); // barrier 1
}
else
{
	__syncthreads(); // barrier 2
}
```

Both of these are different barrier so it will result in hang.
# Memory Model

| Variable Declaration                  | Memory   | Scope  | Lifetime    |
| ------------------------------------- | -------- | ------ | ----------- |
| Automatic variables other than arrays | Register | Thread | Kernel      |
| Automatic array variables             | Local    | Thread | Kernel      |
| `__shared__ int shared_x`             | Shared   | Block  | Kernel      |
| `__device__ int global_x`             | Global   | Grid   | Application |
| `__constant__ int constant_x`         | Constant | Grid   | Application |
The device code can 
- Read/Write per-thread register
- Read/Write per-thread local memory
- Read/Write per-block shared memory
- Read/Write per-grid global memory
- Read only per-grid constant memory 
The host code can
- Read/Write per grid global and constant memory.
![[Pasted image 20250907164451.png]]

Registers are small and fast on-chip local to each thread. There is a fixed amount of registers available on hardware (SM) Increasing the number of register memory (variables) per thread which results in exceeding hardware limit will cause to decrease the number of threads (in some cases blocks) to fit the new register size requirements.

For built-in variables like `threadIdx, blockIdx, blockDim, gridDim` we have "special registers".

When the data can't be fit in a single register and spills over it's stored in local memory. Its threads own private memory. In the hardware its located in global memory. Differences from global memory:
- Addressing is resolved by the compiler => increased instruction count
- Stores are cached in L2

Shared memory is per block fast on-chip memory. Device code has read and write access to it. 
In G80 there were 16 KB of Shared memory and upto 8 blocks were allowed. So say if each block took 5 KB of data then how many blocks will be there in the SM? 

**![The Almost Titan: NVIDIA GeForce GTX 780 Review – Techgage](data:image/png;base64,)**

Global memory is long-latency off-chip memory. However the reads are cached. Random access of global memory causes performance hit. 

Constant memory is short latency, high bandwidth, read only memory. It can be accessed if all threads access the same location. Host can read/write to it. Upto 64 KB. 

```c
__constant__ float constData[256];

int main()
{
	float data[256] // shared
	cudaMemcpyToSymbol(constData, data, sizeof(data)) // copy infromation from the memory to the cuda symbol
	
	cudaMemcpyFromSymbol(data, constData, sizeof(data)) // copy information from the cuda symbol to the memory
}
```

# Faster Memory Transfers
In a GPU we can process much more data but are bottlenecked by data transfer speed between CPU and GPU. In order to optimize this : 
1. Reduce CPU-GPU or GPU-CPU memory transfers
2. Optimize by reducing the overhead of these transfers.
The CPU data allocations are __pageable__ by default. GPU cant access this pageable data directly. First it has to transfer it to __pinned memory__ and then transfer it to device memory. But we can allocate directly to pinned memory in the host using `cudaMallocHost()`

NOTE: `cudaMallocHost()` can fail. 

With this we can achieve maximum practical Pcie bandwidth


# Matrix Multiply Revisited

Take a look at naïve matrix multiplication below 

```c
__global__ void MatrixMultiplication(
	const float* device_m,
	const float* device_n,
	float* device_p,
	const int width
)
{
	int tx = threadIdx.x;
	int ty = threadIdx.y;
	// (x, y) => ty * width + tx;
	
	float pValue = 0;
	
	for(int k = 0; k < width; k++)
	{
		float m = device_m[ty*width + k]; // (k, ty)
		float n = device_n[k*width + tx]; // (tx, k)
		pValue = m+n;
	}
	
	device_p[ty*width + tx] = pValue;
}
```

In order to improve the performance:
- Reuse the row and column using shared memory
- Divide matrix into tiles, each block will compute that tile

![[Pasted image 20250907175818.png]]

![[Pasted image 20250907175457.png]]
```c

__global__ void MatrixMultiplyKernel(
	const float* M, 
	const float* N, 
	float* P, 
	const int width
)
{
	__shared__ float sM[TILE_WIDTH][TILE_WIDTH];
	__shared__ float sN[TILE_WIDTH][TILE_WIDTH];

	int bx       = blockIdx.x;
	int by       = blockIdx.y;
	int tx       = threadIdx.x;
	int ty       = threadIdx.y;
	int col      = bx*width + tx;
	int row      = by*width + ty;
	float pValue = 0;
	
	for(int m = 0; m < WIDTH/TILE_WIDTH; m++)
	{
		sM[ty][tx] = M[row*width + (m*TILE_WIDTH + tx)];
		sN[ty][tx] = N[col + (m*TILE_WIDTH + ty)*width];
		__syncthreads();
		for(int k = 0; k < TILE_WIDTH; k++)
		{
			pValue += sM[ty][k] * sN[k][tx];
		}
		__syncthreads();
	}
	P[row*width + col] = pValue;
}
```
